Regress: Test spoofed user actions and file changes with Center loaded through pipe. Add Express to file.c so Persist can do read modify write of fields.

Release: Use actual user actions to interact with actual file.

Decoration: Add struct and Memory to contain info for custom shaders. Switch on uniform field to decide whether to apply texture or whatever. Fragment shader little language follows graph edges depending on inputs from vertex shader for filling with a constant, copying color or depth or identifier from vertex shader, copying from image buffer, applying texture sampler, calculating from normal, highlighting from adjacent identifiers. Graph edges are constants/inputs in which hypersquare region of constants/inputs, or on which hyperline sids of constants/inputs.

Suite: In plane.lua, share, file, space, plane, side to manipulate polytopes. In space.lua, share, file, space, plane, to display tetrahedron overlaps as they are found and optimized. In line.lua, share, file, space, plane, line, side, to decorate polytopes with sound. In point.lua, share, file, space, plane, line, side, frame, to decorate facets with little language for textures, sound, frames, text, graffiti, permissions, wormholes, transparency. Share connects processes by pipe. Side displays and edits fields in file. Frame displays and edits video and interfaces to hdmi over usbc. 

Name: Call the application pball, for polytope ballet. Higher dimensional spaces are simpler than lower. They teach real analysis with blobs of various sort, like open covering compact and so on, because blobs are easier to understand than numbers. Topology is cool and all, but there is not as much to it as there is to real or even complex numbers. The beauty of two dimensional complex analysis is that complex numbers are simpler than real numbers. What is harder to understand than one dimensional real numbers? The relation or interface of math to reality is zero dimensional and harder to understand than either in isolation. But that’s just metaphysics, so who cares? I just think it’s neat.
